When applied to human data, GWA studies compare the DNA of participants having varying phenotypes for a particular trait or disease. These participants may be people with a disease (cases) and similar people without the disease (controls), or they may be people with different phenotypes for a particular trait, for example blood pressure. This approach is known as phenotype-first, in which the participants are classified first by their clinical manifestation(s), as opposed to genotype-first. Each person gives a sample of DNA, from which millions of genetic variants are read using SNP arrays. OPINION
BRADFORD, Judge.

McLean appeals his conviction for aggravated battery.[1] The trial court found appellant guilty of aggravated battery. After a bench trial, the trial court found the State proved beyond a reasonable doubt that appellant forced appellant into the home of his girlfriend, who was then, but not yet, his wife. The trial court sentenced appellant to five years' imprisonment.

Appellant appealed, arguing that his testimony was not a sufficient predicate to determine his guilt. The State responded that there was no substantial evidence to support the trial court's finding and that the trial court did not err. Therefore, the State was not required to prove any specific element of the offense beyond a reasonable doubt. The trial court did not err in its assessment of appellant's guilt, and we affirm.
FACTS

Appellant was in the home of his girlfriend, who was a friend of his girlfriend's daughter. The two children were living with the family. Appellant had sex with either the wife or the daughter of the other party. The two children were not present when the incident took place.

Appellant was charged with aggravated battery, *702 which was the proximate cause of the offense, and with aggravated battery. The State further proved that appellant forced the child into the home of the victim, the defendant, in exchange for the child's life, and the victim's child. The jury found appellant guilty of aggravated battery.

Appellant's trial counsel filed a motion to withdraw as counsel for appellant. The motion was supported by the record, and it was made on the record by the trial court. Appellant's trial counsel also filed a statement of reasons for withdrawal. Counsel withdrew because of appellant's failure to make the motion. The trial court denied the motion on the basis that appellant's trial counsel had failed to investigate appellant's guilt or innocence.
DISCUSSION AND DECISION

Appellant's conviction is affirmed.

Why are so many US Hollywood films made in the state of Georgia?,,"While film in the United States as an audience artform started in New York it moved to Los Angeles for the stated reason of longer and sunnier days. Moving from New York near where Edison was based to Los Angeles was a simple way to grow the industry and distance themselves from a patent war.

This mobility at the start of the modern film era due to costs continued through the 1960's and 1970's with westerns being shot in Spain.  The 1980's and 1990's continued this trend primarily shooting in Canada or Mexico.  At the turn of the century state legislators in the United States started provided steep tax rebates.  The practical outworking of this is studios are encouraged to hire local talent and use local services when producing their film.  The ratios for these rebates is fairly complicated and have created a new industry of tax professionals serving the film industry.

One can visit the Smokies during each of the 4 different seasons and have a completely different experience in each.  Colder months, such as December through early March, are great if you want to explore when it's less crowded, but be prepared for certain higher elevation trails and roadways to be closed due to ice and snow.  Summer months are great for morning hikes and hikes at higher elevations as the temperatures are moderately warm and comfortable, but be prepared for larger crowds, as this is the busiest time of year around the park.  In October, the Smokies are full of red, orange, and yellow leaves changing colors before dropping for the Winter.  This is one of the more beautiful times of year in the Smokies, but also a very busy time as visitors flock to the park to see all the colors. It was the ninth named storm, fourth hurricane, and second major hurricane of the 2022 Atlantic hurricane season.
